# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1912-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The **1911 Detroit Tigers** had a record of 89–65 and finished in second place in the American League, 131⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] They outscored their opponents 831–776, and drew 484,988 fans to Bennett Park (4th of 8 teams in attendance).
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The 1911 Detroit Tigers opened the season with a phenomenal 21–2 record.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers set the modern record for home wins to start the season, 12–0, and were 51–25 at home but 38–40 on the road.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] They were in first place in the American League every day except one until August 3, 1911.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] After going 59–24, the wheels fell off as the team lost 20 of 30 games in July and were 23–43 in the second half.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers lost 20 of 30 games in July and ended up 131⁄2 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The 1911 Tigers had two of the best batters in baseball in Ty Cobb and Sam Crawford.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] Crawford was not far behind, ranking in the top three in the AL in batting average (.378), slugging (.438), hits (217), total bases (302), and RBIs (115).
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The team ranked second best in the American League in runs scored but the pitching staff's earned run average of 3.73 was the second worst in the league—a full point above the league leading Red Sox' team ERA of 2.74.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] Playing in Bennett Field, with its 8,500-seat wooden grandstand, their home attendance for the entire season was 484,988.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-braves-season] The **1912 Boston Braves season** was the 42nd season of the franchise.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-braves-season] Team owner William Hepburn Russell died after the 1911 season and his stock was bought up by a group including Tammany Hall alderman James Gaffney and former baseball manager John Montgomery Ward.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-braves-season] The team was renamed the **Boston Braves** after the Sachems, also known as "Braves", of Tammany Hall.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The **1912 Boston Red Sox season** was the 12th season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] This was the first year that the team played its home games at Fenway Park.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 105 wins and 47 losses.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The team set the franchise record for highest winning percentage (.691) in a season, which still stands; tied the franchise record for fewest losses in a season, originally set by the 1903 team; and set a franchise record for most wins, which was not surpassed until the 2018 club.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The team then faced the National League (NL) champion New York Giants in the 1912 World Series, which the Red Sox won in eight games to capture the franchise's second World Series.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] One of the deciding plays in the World Series was a muffed fly ball by Giants outfielder Fred Snodgrass, which became known as the "$30,000 muff" in reference to the prize money for the winning team.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] Behind center fielder Tris Speaker and pitcher Smoky Joe Wood, the Red Sox led the league in runs scored and fewest runs allowed.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] Speaker was third in batting and was voted league Most Valuable Player.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] Wood won 34 games, including a record 16 in a row.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] Although the pitching staff was satisfactory, the only star pitcher was Wood, while the only star in the starting lineup was Speaker.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] Little-known third baseman Larry Gardner was the next best hitter, while future Hall of Famer Harry Hooper had a poor offensive season.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox made several transactions during the 1912 offseason.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox sold two players to the Chicago White Sox during the offseason: Jack Fournier on February 6 and Eddie Cicotte on July 9.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] Later in the year, on November 25, Hugh Bradley was sold to the Jersey City Giants minor league baseball team of the International League.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] Paul Saints announce the purchase of outfielder Joe Riggert from the Red Sox.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] January 6, 1912: The Red Sox trade players Harold Janvrin, Martin McHale, Walter Lonergan, Hap Myers, Jack Thoney, and Billy Purtell to the Jersey City Skeeters in exchange for catcher Forrest Cady.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] February, 1912: The Red Sox sell infielder Rip Williams to the New York Highlanders.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] On February 23, the Highlanders sent Williams to the Washington Nationals.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] February 6, 1912: The Chicago White Sox announce the purchase of infielder Jack Fournier from the Red Sox.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The new Red Sox home stadium, Fenway Park opened on April 20, the same day as Navin Field in Detroit opened.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] It was supposed to be opened on April 18 (like Navin Field) but it rained in both cities on that day.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] This first Major-League game played at Fenway Park pitted the Red Sox against the New York Highlanders, with the Red Sox winning by a score of 7–6, and New York's Harry Wolter being the first player to earn a hit in the park.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] On April 26, Hugh Bradley became the first player to hit a home run over the Green Monster at Fenway Park.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] It was his only home run of the 1912 season, and one of only two he hit in his career, which spanned five seasons.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] June 25: The Cleveland Naps sell infielder Neal Ball to the Red Sox for $2500.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] On April 11, 1912, the Red Sox defeated the New York Highlanders 5–3 in an away game.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The 1912 World Series was played between the New York Giants of the NL and the Red Sox of the AL.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox won in eight games, 4–3, having played the Giants to a tie in Game 2.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-brooklyn-trolley-dodgers-season] The **1912 Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers** finished in seventh place with a 58–95 record.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-cubs-season] The **1912 Chicago Cubs season** was the 41st season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 37th in the National League and the 20th at West Side Park.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished third in the National League with a record of 91–59.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-cubs-season] Third baseman Heinie Zimmerman led the circuit in home runs, batting average, and slugging percentage.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-cubs-season] (a) Baseball Reference and Retrosheet have his 1912 RBI total at 104.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-cubs-season] Baseball Almanac and The Baseball Cube have his RBI total at 99.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-white-sox-season] In 1912, the **Chicago White Sox** debuted one of the most enduring and famous logos in baseball – a large "S" in a Roman-style font, with a small "O" inside the top loop of the "S" and a small "X" inside the bottom loop.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-white-sox-season] This is the logo associated with the 1917 World Series championship team, and the 1919 Black Sox.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-white-sox-season] With a couple of brief interruptions, the dark blue logo with the large "S" lasted through 1938 (but continued in a modified block style into the 1940s).
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-chicago-white-sox-season] Through the 1940s, the White Sox team colors were primarily navy blue trimmed with red.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1912 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished fourth in the National League with a record of 75–78, 29 games behind the New York Giants.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] This was the inaugural year of the Reds' new stadium, Redland Field, later known as Crosley Field.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds moved into a new stadium beginning in the 1912 season, as the club moved from the Palace of the Fans to Redland Field.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The new stadium had a seating capacity of 20,696, which was up from the 12,000 capacity at Palace of the Fans.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati replaced their manager Clark Griffith, following a disappointing 1911 season, and replaced him with Hank O'Day.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] O'Day, a former pitcher from 1884 to 1890, had a 73–110 record and a 3.74 ERA in his career.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] O'Day was also a former umpire, and notably was behind the plate in the first ever World Series game in 1903.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] He was also the home plate umpire who made the initial ruling on Merkle's Boner.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] He did not have any previous managerial experience.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds sold shortstop Tom Downey to the Philadelphia Phillies on December 29.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati shifted third baseman Eddie Grant to shortstop, where he split playing time with Jimmy Esmond, as the club named Art Phelan their new third baseman.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Phelan, only 23 years old, saw limited action with Cincinnati in 1910, before spending the 1911 season in the minors.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati had a tough season offensively, as the club ranked last in batting average (.256), on base percentage (.323), hits (1310), doubles (183) and home runs (21).
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] First baseman Dick Hoblitzell hit .294 and had 85 RBI, however, his home run total dropped from eleven in 1911 to only two in 1912.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Outfielder Armando Marsans led the Reds with a .317 batting average, while hitting one home run and 38 RBI in 110 games.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Outfielder Bob Bescher led the National League in stolen bases with 67, and he had a .281 batting average with four home runs and 38 RBI, and scored 120 runs.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Outfielder Mike Mitchell batted .283 with four home runs and 78 RBI in 147 games.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The pitching rotation was led by Rube Benton, as in his first full season as a starting pitcher, he appeared in a National League high 50 games, starting 39 of them.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Benton had a record of 18–20 with a 3.10 ERA while pitching 302 innings, striking out 162 batters and had 22 complete games.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] George Suggs led Cincinnati in wins, as he was 19–16 with a 2.94 ERA in 42 games, pitching 303 innings and recording a team high 25 complete games.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Art Fromme finished the year with a 16–18 record in 43 games, throwing 296 innings and 23 complete games, while having a team best 2.74 ERA.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The club got off to a surprising start of the season, as Cincinnati had a 22–6 record in their first 28 games, leading the National League by 1.5 games over the New York Giants.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds lost 10 of their next 11 games to fall out of first place, and could never recover.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati would eventually fall under .500, and finished the season with a 75–78 record, an improvement of five games over 1911, but finished 29 games behind the New York Giants for the pennant.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] The **1912 Detroit Tigers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] It involved the Tigers finishing sixth in the American League.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] It was the team's first season in Tiger Stadium (then known as Navin Field).
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] On April 20, 1912, Navin Field opened the same day as Fenway Park.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] It was supposed to be opened on April 18 (like Fenway Park) but it rained in both cities on that day.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] Ty Cobb scored the first run in Tiger Stadium by stealing home.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] On May 18, 1912, the Tigers players went on strike to protest the suspension of star center fielder Ty Cobb, who had gone into the stands on May 15 to attack a disabled fan who had been abusing him.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] Rather than forfeit the next game, the Tigers sent out a team of replacement players, mostly local college and sandlot players but also including Tigers coaches Joe Sugden and 48-year-old Deacon McGuire.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] Manager Hughie Jennings also entered the game as a pinch hitter.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] Starting pitcher Allan Travers gave up 24 runs on 26 hits in a complete game loss, both American League records.
[src:1912-detroit-tigers-season/1912-detroit-tigers-season] On July 4, 1912, George Mullin threw the first no-hitter in Detroit Tigers history.
